Statistics

Problem Statement for "KRectangleIntersection"

Problem Statement

You are given four int[]s, each with the same number of elements: xl, yl, xh, and yh. These describe a collection of rectangles. The sides of each rectangle are parallel to the coordinate axes. For each valid index i, one of the rectangles has its lower left corner at (xl[i], yl[i]) and its upper right corner at (xh[i], yh[i]).

Given an int k, find the largest possible area of the intersection of k of these rectangles.

Definition

Class:
KRectangleIntersection
Method:
maxIntersection
Parameters:
int[], int[], int[], int[], int
Returns:
long
Method signature:
long maxIntersection(int[] xl, int[] yl, int[] xh, int[] yh, int k)
(be sure your method is public)

Constraints

  • xl, yl, xh, yh will all have the same number of elements.
  • The number of elements in xl will be between 1 and 200, inclusive.
  • Each element in xl, yl, xh, yh will be between 1 and 10^9, inclusive.
  • For each valid i, xl[i] will be smaller than xh[i] and yl[i] will be smaller than yh[i] .
  • k will be between 1 and the number of rectangles, inclusive.

Examples

  1. {1, 2, 3}

    {1, 2, 3}

    {10, 9, 8}

    {10, 9, 8}

    2

    Returns: 49

    Three rectangles: one with corners at (1,1) and (10,10), one with corners at (2,2) and (9,9), and one with corners at (3,3) and (8,8). The optimal solution is clearly to take the first two rectangles.
